In $ \triangle ABC$, we have $ \angle C \equal{} 3 \angle A$, $ a \equal{} 27$, and $ c \equal{} 48$.  What is $ b$?

[asy]size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
pair A=origin, B=(14,0), C=(10,6);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$a$", B--C, dir(B--C)*dir(-90));
label("$b$", A--C, dir(C--A)*dir(-90));
label("$c$", A--B, dir(A--B)*dir(-90));
[/asy]

$ \textbf{(A)}\ 33 \qquad \textbf{(B)}\ 35 \qquad \textbf{(C)}\ 37 \qquad \textbf{(D)}\ 39 \qquad \textbf{(E)}\ \text{not uniquely determined}$

\section*{Problem 3 - 051013}

How does the measure of the surface area of a cone, whose axial section is an equilateral triangle, compare to the measure of the surface area of a cylinder with a square axial section, if the measure of the volumes of both bodies is equal?

In both figures, the same units of measurement are assumed.
